Wed 6 Jul: 1 / 24 / 25 / 50
Thu 7 Jul: 8 / 42 / 50 / 44 (new case definition)
Fri 8 Jul: 1 / 9 / 10 / 44

Total cases: 3774 with 44 deaths -- 1.16 per cent case fatality rate.
The new case definition resulted in lower total cases and deaths but
did not affect case fatality rate.

The cases do not necessarily reflect date of onset of disease but
rather when the diagnosis was made and reported. The number of newly
reported cases per day clearly decreased from the corresponding day in
the previous week. - Mod.LL]

******
[2] Denmark ex Germany: secondary cases
Date: Thu 7 Jul 2011
Source: Expatica [edited]
http://www.expatica.com/de/news/german-news/two-danes-get-german-e-coli-strain-from-relatives-official_161538.html


A 6 year old girl and a 60 year old woman contracted _E. coli_
[O104:H4] infection that has killed some 50 people mainly in Germany
from relatives who traveled there, a Danish laboratory said on Thu 7
Jul 2011.

The bacteria are most often transmitted through food consumption, but
"since the infection can transmit from person to person through food
or hands contaminated with fecal matter, these new cases emphasise the
importance of good hygiene when in contact with such patients," the
statement added.

The latest cases, detected in mid-June 2011 and the beginning of July
2011, bring to 25 the number of Danes who have fallen ill with the
bacteria, including 10 who have contracted hemolytic uremic syndrome
(HUS), a kidney complaint caused by EHEC [enterohemorrhagic _E.
coli_], according to SSI [Statens Serum Institut].

